                  <li class="program-course">
            <a href="/study/2014-2015/courses/hist-440" class="program-course-title">
              HIST 440 Fiction and History (3 credits)              <!---->            </a>
            <div class="program-course-description">
              <div class="program-course-description-inner">
                <div id="node-27716" class=" clearfix">
  
  
  
  <div class="meta">
    <p>Offered by: History and Classical Studies (<a href="/study/2014-2015/node/607">Faculty of Arts</a>)</p>
      </div>

  <div class="content">
    <h3>Overview</h3>

    <p>
      History              : This course examines why and how books are classified as fiction or history. Topics include: social expectations and uses of literature; evidence and verification; the author as authority. Readings include history and fiction from various historical periods, and relevant scholarship.          </p>

    <p class="catalog-terms">
      Terms:              Winter 2015          </p>

    <p class="catalog-instructors">
      Instructors:                        Nancy F Partner (Winter)                  </p>

    
          <ul class="catalog-notes">
              <li>Prerequisite: 6 credits at the 300 level in either history or literature</li>
            </ul>
      </div>

